ðŸ”¹ What is a Derived Class?
Imagine you have a big toy car ðŸš—. Now, you want to make a new toy car ðŸš™ 
that is similar but has extra features like a cool spoiler or a faster engine.

In C++, we can create a new class from an existing class. This is called Inheritance, 
and the new class is called a Derived Class.

ðŸ”¹ Example: Parent and Child Relationship
ðŸ“Œ Think of it like this:

Parent Class (Base Class) = A general toy car ðŸš—
Child Class (Derived Class) = A new version with a spoiler ðŸš™
ðŸ’¡ A Derived Class inherits everything from the Parent Class!

ðŸ”¹ Example: Creating a Derived Class in C++
Let's say we have a "Vehicle" class and a "Car" class that inherits from it.

    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;
    // Base class (Parent)
    class Vehicle {
        public:
            int wheels = 4;
            void start() {
                cout << "Vehicle is starting..." << endl;
            }
    };

    // Derived class (Child)
    class Car : public Vehicle {
        public:
            void honk() {
            cout << "Beep! Beep! ðŸš—" << endl;
        }
    };

    int main() {
        Car myCar;
        myCar.start();  // Inherited from Vehicle
        myCar.honk();   // Defined in Car

        cout << "Car has " << myCar.wheels << " wheels!" << endl;
        return 0;
    }

ðŸ”¹ Output:
    Vehicle is starting...
    Beep! Beep! ðŸš—
    Car has 4 wheels!

ðŸš€ Whatâ€™s happening here?
The Car class inherits start() and wheels from the Vehicle class.
The Car class adds a new function honk().
ðŸ”¹ Types of Inheritance (How Classes Can Be Derived)
In C++, you can inherit classes in different ways:

1ï¸âƒ£ Public Inheritance (Most Common âœ…)
Everything public in the Parent stays public in the Child.
Everything protected in the Parent stays protected in the Child.

    class Parent {
        public:
            int a;
        protected:
            int b;
        private:
            int c;
    };

    class Child : public Parent {
        // a is public
        // b is protected
        // c is NOT inherited (private members are NOT inherited)
    };

2ï¸âƒ£ Protected Inheritance
Everything public in the Parent becomes protected in the Child.
Everything protected in the Parent stays protected in the Child.

class Child : protected Parent {
    // a becomes protected
    // b stays protected
    // c is NOT inherited
};
3ï¸âƒ£ Private Inheritance
Everything public and protected in the Parent becomes private in the Child.

class Child : private Parent {
    // a becomes private
    // b becomes private
    // c is NOT inherited
};
ðŸ’¡ Public inheritance is the most used type!

ðŸ”¹ Overriding Functions in Derived Classes
Sometimes, a Derived Class needs to change the behavior of a function from the Base Class.

ðŸ“Œ Example:

    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;
    class Animal {
        public:
        void makeSound() {
            cout << "Some generic animal sound..." << endl;
        }
    };

    class Dog : public Animal {
        public:
        void makeSound() {  // Overrides the function
            cout << "Woof! Woof! ðŸ¶" << endl;
        }
    };

    int main() {
        Dog myDog;
        myDog.makeSound();  // Calls the overridden function
        return 0;
    }

ðŸ”¹ Output:
    Woof! Woof! ðŸ¶

ðŸš€ The Derived Class changes the function from the Parent Class!

ðŸ”¹ Calling Parent Class Functions
Sometimes, you might want to call the Parent Classâ€™s function inside the Derived Class.

ðŸ“Œ Example:
    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;
    class Animal {
        public:
        void makeSound() {
            cout << "Some generic animal sound..." << endl;
        }
    };

    class Dog : public Animal {
        public:
        void makeSound() {
            Animal::makeSound();  // Calls Parent Class function
            cout << "Woof! Woof! ðŸ¶" << endl;
        }
    };

    int main() {
        Dog myDog;
        myDog.makeSound();
        return 0;
    }
ðŸ”¹ Output:
    Some generic animal sound...
    Woof! Woof! ðŸ¶
ðŸš€ Now, both Parent and Child functions are called!

ðŸ”¹ Constructors in Derived Classes
When you create a Derived Class object, the Base Class constructor runs first.

ðŸ“Œ Example:


#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Animal {
public:
    Animal() {
        cout << "Animal created!" << endl;
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal {
public:
    Dog() {
        cout << "Dog created!" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Dog myDog;
    return 0;
}
ðŸ”¹ Output:


Animal created!
Dog created!
ðŸš€ The Parent Constructor runs first!

ðŸ”¹ Summary
âœ” Derived Classes inherit from Base Classes.
âœ” public, protected, and private inheritance affect visibility.
âœ” Functions can be overridden in Derived Classes.
âœ” Constructors in Base Classes run first.

